To Art and our silent brothers:<br><br>
&quot;Tawamiciya,&quot; asserts that one should belong to himself free of other men.  It does not advocate total separation from others.  However, it does assign responsibility to one's self for his actions.  I will listen to the words of others and decide for myself which path that I shall take.  When my independent actions and values are in agreement with those of my brothers, then I am likely to be accepted and live in harmony with external forces.<br>
I am not forced into oneness... I seek it with those I admire.  Their demonstrated values in wisdom, courage, self sacrifice, and loyalty draw me to them.<br>
Common ground shared with other warriors evokes a powerful love and sense of loyalty that is difficult to define.  Desiring that those I love reciprocate, my conduct must fall within certain standards of performance and committment.  These tough and exacting parameters are often refered to as honor.<br>
You are &quot;Hunka,&quot;  my relative by choice.  You are my brother.<br><br>
Hecito yelo, Was'te<br><br>
Humming Eagle
